{"cursor":"3696","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":":\"Section break\" redirects here. For the term's use in overhead lines, see\n:[[Overhead lines#Breaks]].\n'', showing an ornate section break on the lower left page created from\nasterisks. It is used to signal a pause for the reader and a transition in the\nnarrative.]] In books and documents, a 'section' is a subdivision, especially of\na chapter.\n\nSections are visually separated from each other with a 'section break',\ntypically consisting of extra space between the sections. They are a concern in\nthe process of typography and pagination, where it may be desirable to have a\npage break follow a section break for the sake of aesthetics or readability.\n\nIn fiction, sections often represent scenes, and accordingly the space\nseparating them is sometimes also called a 'scene break'.\n","linknr":116,"url":"Section_(typography)","recorded":1362671737,"links":11,"instances":["fiction","speed","literature","drama","books","bookbinding","typography","fiction","typography","psychology"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Writing","Book design","Book terminology"],"headings":["Section form and numbering","Flourished section breaks","See also"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/92/Section_break_01_by_Pengo.jpg/220px-Section_break_01_by_Pengo.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["transition","fiction"],["chapter","books"],["scene","drama"],["point_of_view","fiction"],["mood","psychology"],["tone","literature"],["pace","speed"],["transition","fiction"],["section_51(xxvi_of_the_australian_constitution"],["asterism","typography"],["fleuron","typography"],["section","bookbinding"]],"members":["transition","pace","tone","sc